04214nam a22006735i 9780691183909DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20182018nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911839097 a10.23943/97806911839092doi  a(DE-B1597)501223  a(OCoLC)1043913727  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPHI0070002bisacsh04a1882231 aEpictetus, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow to Be Free :bAn Ancient Guide to the Stoic Life /cEpictetus. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAncient Wisdom for Modern Readers00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tABOUT THE ENCHEIRIDION -- tHow to Be Free -- tThe Encheiridion -- tFrom the Discourses -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tGLOSSARY -- tFURTHER READING -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA superb new edition of Epictetus's famed handbook on Stoicism-translated by one of the world's leading authorities on Stoic philosophyBorn a slave, the Roman Stoic philosopher Epictetus (c. 55-135 AD) taught that mental freedom is supreme, since it can liberate one anywhere, even in a prison. In How to Be Free, A. A. Long-one of the world's leading authorities on Stoicism and a pioneer in its remarkable contemporary revival-provides a superb new edition of Epictetus's celebrated guide to the Stoic philosophy of life (the Encheiridion) along with a selection of related reflections in his Discourses.Freedom, for Epictetus, is not a human right or a political prerogative but a psychological and ethical achievement, a gift that we alone can bestow on ourselves. We can all be free, but only if we learn to assign paramount value to what we can control (our motivations and reactions), treat what we cannot control with equanimity, and view our circumstances as opportunities to do well and be well, no matter what happens to us through misfortune or the actions of other people.How to Be Free features splendid new translations and the original Greek on facing pages, a compelling introduction that sets Epictetus in context and describes the importance of Stoic freedom today, and an invaluable glossary of key words and concepts. The result is an unmatched introduction to this powerful method of managing emotions and handling life's situations, from the most ordinary to the most demanding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Free Will & Determinism.2bisacsh1 aLong, Anthony.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060659140uhttps://doi.org/10.23943/9780691183909zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691183909423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691183909/original  a978-3-11-060659-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK